.TH "fuse\-archive" "1" "April 2026" "fuse\-archive 1.21" "User Manual"
.PD
.SH NAME
\f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] \- Mount archives as a read\-only FUSE file
system.
.PD
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PD 0
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]] \f[I]archive\f[R]
[\f[I]mount_point\f[R]]
.PD 0
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]] \f[I]archive\f[R] \&...
\f[I]mount_point\f[R]
.PD
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] serves one or several archives or compressed
files (e.g., \f[CR]foo.tar\f[R], \f[CR]foo.tar.gz\f[R],
\f[CR]foo.xz\f[R], or \f[CR]foo.zip\f[R]) as a read\-only \c
.UR https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Filesystem_in_Userspace
FUSE
.UE \c
\ file system.
.PD
.PP
It is similar to \c
.UR https://github.com/google/mount-zip
\f[B]mount\-zip\f[R]
.UE \c
\ and \c
.UR https://bitbucket.org/agalanin/fuse-zip
\f[B]fuse\-zip\f[R]
.UE \c
\ but supports a larger range of archive or compressed file formats.
.PD
.PP
It is similar to \c
.UR https://github.com/cybernoid/archivemount
\f[B]archivemount\f[R]
.UE \c
\ but can be much faster (see the Performance section below), although
it can only mount read\-only, not read\-write.
.PD
.PP
\f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] automatically creates the target mount point if
needed and automatically removes it when the file system is unmounted.
If the mount point already existed before \f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] was
started, it is not removed.
.PD
.PP
If no mount point is specified, \f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] uses the name of
the archive (without its filename extension) as a mount point in the
current working directory.
If that directory already exists, it will try to create one with a
numeric suffix (e.g., \f[CR]archive (1)\f[R]).
.PD
.SH OPTIONS
.PD
.TP
\f[B]\-\-help\f[R] or \f[B]\-h\f[R]
Print help.
.PD
.TP
\f[B]\-\-version\f[R] or \f[B]\-V\f[R]
Print version info.
.PD
.TP
\f[B]\-o quiet\f[R] or \f[B]\-q\f[R]
Print fewer log messages.
.PD
.TP
\f[B]\-o verbose\f[R] or \f[B]\-v\f[R]
Print more log messages.
.PD
.TP
\f[B]\-o redact\f[R]
Redact file names from log messages.
.PD
.TP
\f[B]\-o force\f[R]
Continue despite errors.
.PD
.TP
\f[B]\-o maxfilters=N\f[R]
Maximum number of filters per archive (default is 1).
.PD
.TP
\f[B]\-o lazycache\f[R]
Incremental caching of uncompressed data.
.PD
.TP
\f[B]\-o nocache\f[R]
No caching of uncompressed data.
.PD
.TP
\f[B]\-o memcache\f[R]
Caching in memory (Linux only).
.PD
.TP
\f[B]\-o nomerge\f[R]
Do not merge multiple archives on top of each other.
Instead, create a subdirectory for each archive inside the mount point.
.PD
.TP
\f[B]\-o notrim\f[R]
Do not trim the base of the tree.
Keep all the intermediate directories as specified in the archive(s).
.PD
.TP
\f[B]\-o nodirs\f[R]
No directories.
Flatten the archive structure by presenting all its files in its root
directory.
This might make sense if you\[cq]re not interested in the archive tree
structure, but only in its file data, e.g., for malware scanning.
.PD
.TP
\f[B]\-o nospecials\f[R]
Hide special files (FIFOs, sockets, devices).
.PD
.TP
\f[B]\-o nosymlinks\f[R]
Hide symbolic links.
.PD
.TP
\f[B]\-o noholes\f[R]
Do not report holes in sparse files.
.PD
.TP
\f[B]\-o nohardlinks\f[R]
Do not report files with multiple hard links.
.PD
.TP
\f[B]\-o noxattrs\f[R]
Do not report extended attributes.
.PD
.TP
\f[B]\-o dmask=M\f[R]
Directory permission mask in octal (default is 0022).
.PD
.TP
\f[B]\-o fmask=M\f[R]
File permission mask in octal (default is 0022).
.PD
.TP
\f[B]\-o uid=N\f[R]
Set the file owner of all the items in the mounted archive (default is
the current user).
.PD
.TP
\f[B]\-o gid=N\f[R]
Set the file group of all the items in the mounted archive (default is
the current group).
.PD
.TP
\f[B]\-o default_permissions\f[R]
Use the file owner (UID), group (GID), and permissions stored with each
item in the archive.
.PD
.TP
\f[B]\-f\f[R]
Foreground mode.
.PD
.TP
\f[B]\-d\f[R]
Foreground mode with debug output.
.PD
.SH USAGE EXAMPLES
Mount a single archive:
.IP
.EX
$ fuse\-archive foobar.tar.gz mnt
.EE
.PD
.PP
The mounted archive can be explored and read using any application:
.IP
.EX
$ tree mnt
mnt
└── foo
    └── bar.txt

1 directory, 1 file

$ cat mnt/foo/bar.txt
Hello, world!
.EE
.PD
.PP
Mount multiple archives into the same mount point (merged view):
.IP
.EX
$ fuse\-archive archive1.zip archive2.tar.bz2 mnt
.EE
.PD
.PP
Mount multiple archives as separate subdirectories:
.IP
.EX
$ fuse\-archive \-o nomerge archive1.zip archive2.7z mnt
$ ls mnt
archive1 archive2
.EE
.PD
.PP
Consult a GPG\-encrypted file securely without decrypting it to disk:
.IP
.EX
$ fuse\-archive secret.txt.gpg mnt
Password >
$ cat mnt/secret.txt
.EE
.PD
.PP
When finished, unmount the file system:
.IP
.EX
$ umount mnt
.EE
.PD
