.SH ARCHIVE FORMATS
\f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] is built on top of the \c
.UR https://libarchive.org
\f[B]libarchive\f[R]
.UE \c
\ library.
It supports a wide variety of archive formats and compression methods,
either natively through \f[B]libarchive\f[R] or by invoking external
filter programs.
.PD
.PP
The exact set of supported formats depends on:
.PD 0
.IP \[bu] 2
The version and build\-time configuration of the \f[B]libarchive\f[R]
library.
.PD 0
.IP \[bu] 2
The availability of external filter programs in your system\[cq]s
\f[CR]PATH\f[R].
.PD
.PP
To see the version of \f[B]libarchive\f[R] and other libraries linked
with your build of \f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R], use the
\f[CR]\-\-version\f[R] option:
.IP
.EX
$ fuse\-archive \-\-version
.EE
.PD
.SS Filename Extensions
\f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] primarily determines an archive\[cq]s format
from its filename extension.
It recognizes the following:
.PD 0
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]Archive formats\f[R]: \f[CR]7z\f[R], \f[CR]7zip\f[R], \f[CR]a\f[R],
\f[CR]ar\f[R], \f[CR]cab\f[R], \f[CR]cpio\f[R], \f[CR]deb\f[R],
\f[CR]iso\f[R], \f[CR]iso9660\f[R], \f[CR]jar\f[R], \f[CR]mtree\f[R],
\f[CR]rar\f[R], \f[CR]rpm\f[R], \f[CR]tar\f[R], \f[CR]war\f[R],
\f[CR]warc\f[R], \f[CR]xar\f[R], \f[CR]zip\f[R], \f[CR]zipx\f[R].
.PD 0
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]ZIP\-based formats\f[R]: \f[CR]crx\f[R], \f[CR]odf\f[R],
\f[CR]odg\f[R], \f[CR]odp\f[R], \f[CR]ods\f[R], \f[CR]odt\f[R],
\f[CR]docx\f[R], \f[CR]ppsx\f[R], \f[CR]pptx\f[R], \f[CR]xlsx\f[R].
.PD 0
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]Compressed TARs\f[R]: \f[CR]tb2\f[R], \f[CR]tbr\f[R],
\f[CR]tbz\f[R], \f[CR]tbz2\f[R], \f[CR]tz2\f[R], \f[CR]tgz\f[R],
\f[CR]tlz\f[R], \f[CR]tlz4\f[R], \f[CR]tlzma\f[R], \f[CR]txz\f[R],
\f[CR]tz\f[R], \f[CR]taz\f[R], \f[CR]tzs\f[R], \f[CR]tzst\f[R],
\f[CR]tzstd\f[R].
.PD 0
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]Compression filters\f[R]: \f[CR]br\f[R], \f[CR]brotli\f[R],
\f[CR]bz2\f[R], \f[CR]bzip2\f[R], \f[CR]grz\f[R], \f[CR]grzip\f[R],
\f[CR]gz\f[R], \f[CR]gzip\f[R], \f[CR]lha\f[R], \f[CR]lrz\f[R],
\f[CR]lrzip\f[R], \f[CR]lz\f[R], \f[CR]lz4\f[R], \f[CR]lzip\f[R],
\f[CR]lzma\f[R], \f[CR]lzo\f[R], \f[CR]lzop\f[R], \f[CR]xz\f[R],
\f[CR]z\f[R], \f[CR]zst\f[R], \f[CR]zstd\f[R].
.PD 0
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]ASCII encoding filters\f[R]: \f[CR]b64\f[R], \f[CR]base64\f[R],
\f[CR]uu\f[R].
.PD 0
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]Encryption filters\f[R]: \f[CR]asc\f[R], \f[CR]gpg\f[R],
\f[CR]pgp\f[R].
.PD
.PP
If the filename extension is not recognized, \f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R]
will attempt to detect the format by examining the file\[cq]s byte
contents.
.PD
.SS External Filter Programs
For some formats and encodings, \f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] relies on the
following external programs being available in your \f[CR]PATH\f[R]:
\f[CR]base64\f[R], \f[CR]brotli\f[R], \f[CR]compress\f[R],
\f[CR]gpg\f[R], \f[CR]lrzip\f[R], and \f[CR]lzop\f[R].
.PD
.SH ARCHIVE TREE STRUCTURE
By default, \f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] optimizes the presentation of the
mounted archives by merging them and trimming redundant top\-level
directories.
This behavior can be modified with the \f[CR]\-o nomerge\f[R] and
\f[CR]\-o notrim\f[R] options.
.PD
.SS Merging Multiple Archives
When mounting several archives, \f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] merges their
contents into a single unified directory tree by default.
If multiple archives contain the same file path, the files are
deduplicated by adding a numeric suffix (e.g., \f[CR]file (1).txt\f[R]).
.PD
.PP
With the \f[CR]\-o nomerge\f[R] option, \f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] creates
a separate subdirectory for each archive at the root of the mount point,
named after the archive\[cq]s filename.
.PD
.SS Trimming the Base Tree
\f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] automatically \[lq]trims\[rq] the common base
directory of the archive to provide more direct access to its contents.
For example, if an archive contains only \f[CR]a/b/c/file.txt\f[R], it
will be presented as \f[CR]file.txt\f[R] at the root of the mount point.
.PD
.PP
The \f[CR]\-o notrim\f[R] option disables this behavior, preserving all
intermediate directories as they are recorded in the archive.
.PD
