.SH ENCRYPTION
\f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] supports two distinct types of encryption:
native archive encryption and GPG\-based encryption.
.PD
.SS Native Archive Encryption
Some archive formats (such as ZIP) have native encryption capabilities
built\-in.
\f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] can leverage these when supported by the
underlying \f[B]libarchive\f[R] library.
.PD 0
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]ZIP\f[R]: Supported (may require specific \f[B]libarchive\f[R]
build options).
.PD 0
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]7Z and RAR\f[R]: Native encryption for these formats is currently
\f[B]not\f[R] supported.
.PD
.PP
When mounting a natively encrypted archive, \f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] will
securely prompt for a password in the terminal.
You can also pipe the password to \f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R]\[cq]s standard
input.
.PD
.SS GPG Encryption
\f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] also supports archives and individual files
encrypted with \c
.UR https://gnupg.org/
GnuPG
.UE \c
\ (e.g., \f[CR]archive.tar.gpg\f[R], \f[CR]archive.7z.pgp\f[R], or
\f[CR]romeo.txt.asc\f[R]).
This is handled by invoking the external \f[CR]gpg\f[R] command\-line
tool.
.PD
.PP
Using GPG encryption is particularly useful for consulting sensitive
documents without having to store a decrypted copy on the local disk,
which avoids the risk of leaving confidential data behind in temporary
folders.
.PD
.PP
When mounting a GPG\-encrypted item, \f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] leverages
your existing GnuPG configuration and environment:
.PD 0
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]Passphrase Management\f[R]: It can work with \f[CR]gpg\-agent\f[R]
to reuse cached passphrases.
.PD 0
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]Secure Prompting\f[R]: It can use \f[CR]pinentry\f[R] to securely
prompt for passphrases via your preferred method (GUI or terminal).
.PD 0
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]Hardware Support\f[R]: It supports decryption via hardware tokens
(like YubiKeys) if they are configured in your system\[cq]s GnuPG setup.
.PD 0
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]Nested Encodings\f[R]: It can handle multiple layers of compression
and encryption (e.g., \f[CR]archive.tar.gz.gpg\f[R]).
Use the \f[CR]\-o maxfilters\f[R] option to support these scenarios.
.PD
.PP
Ensure that the \f[CR]gpg\f[R] program is installed and available in
your \f[CR]PATH\f[R].
.PD
.SH CACHING
\f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] only does the minimum amount of work required to
serve the requested data.
It offers several caching strategies and storage options to balance
performance, mount time, and resource usage.
.PD
.SS Caching Strategies
The following strategies are mutually exclusive.
If none is specified, pre\-emptive caching is used by default.
.PD
.SS Pre\-emptive Caching (Default)
By default, \f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] decompresses and caches the whole
archive before serving its contents.
The cost of decompression is incurred upfront at mount time, ensuring
that subsequent access to any file is instantaneous and supports
efficient random access.
.PD
.SS Incremental Caching (\f[CR]\-o lazycache\f[R])
With \f[CR]\-o lazycache\f[R], \f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] decompresses data
on\-the\-go as it is requested by applications.
This results in nearly instant mounting for archives that support random
access to metadata (such as ZIP, 7Z, or RAR).
Once a section of the archive has been read, it is cached for future
access.
.PD
.PP
Note that for solidly compressed archives (e.g., \f[CR].tar.gz\f[R],
\f[CR].tar.xz\f[R]) or encrypted archives, the entire file must still be
processed at mount time to retrieve the file list, which may take some
time for very large archives.
.PD
.SS No Caching (\f[CR]\-o nocache\f[R])
The \f[CR]\-o nocache\f[R] option disables long\-term caching.
\f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] will use a small rolling buffer in memory to
serve data.
This minimizes disk and memory usage but can be significantly slower for
non\-sequential access patterns or if the same files are read
repeatedly, as data may need to be re\-decompressed.
.PD
.SS Storage Options
.PD
.SS Disk Caching (Default)
By default, decompressed data is cached in an anonymous temporary file
(in \f[CR]$TMPDIR\f[R] or \f[CR]/tmp\f[R]).
This cache can use a significant amount of disk space but is
automatically deleted when the archive is unmounted.
.PD
.SS Memory Caching (\f[CR]\-o memcache\f[R])
The \f[CR]\-o memcache\f[R] option instructs \f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] to
store the cache in RAM instead of a temporary file.
This provides the highest performance but can consume a large amount of
memory.
It can be used with both pre\-emptive and incremental caching
strategies.
This option is only available on Linux.
.PD
.SH ADVANCED OPTIONS
.PD
.SS Handling Errors (\f[CR]\-o force\f[R])
The \f[CR]\-o force\f[R] option allows \f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] to
continue mounting an archive even if some errors are encountered.
This includes:
.PD 0
.IP \[bu] 2
Wrong or missing decryption passwords.
.PD 0
.IP \[bu] 2
Unsupported compression or encryption methods.
.PD
.PP
In these cases, files that cannot be correctly processed will still be
listed in the directory tree, but attempting to read them will result in
an Input/Output error (EIO).
.PD
.SS Nested Encodings (\f[CR]\-o maxfilters=N\f[R])
Some archives may have multiple layers of compression or encryption
(e.g., \f[CR]archive.tar.gz.gpg\f[R]).
By default, \f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] only processes one layer of
filtering.
.PD
.PP
To mount archives with nested encodings, you must increase the
\f[CR]\-o maxfilters\f[R] value (e.g., \f[CR]\-o maxfilters=2\f[R]).
.PD
.SS Permissions and Ownership
By default, \f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] presents all files as being owned by
the current user and group, with standard read permissions.
.PD
.SS User and Group IDs (\f[CR]\-o uid=N\f[R], \f[CR]\-o gid=N\f[R])
You can explicitly set the owner and group of all items in the mounted
archive using the \f[CR]\-o uid\f[R] and \f[CR]\-o gid\f[R] options with
the desired numerical IDs.
.PD
.SS Using Archive Permissions (\f[CR]\-o default_permissions\f[R])
The \f[CR]\-o default_permissions\f[R] option instructs
\f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] to use the exact UID, GID, and Unix permission
bits stored within the archive for each item.
This includes support for special bits such as \f[B]SUID\f[R],
\f[B]SGID\f[R], and \f[B]SVTX\f[R] (sticky bit).
.PD
.SS Permission Masks (\f[CR]\-o dmask=M\f[R], \f[CR]\-o fmask=M\f[R])
You can apply an octal permission mask to directories (\f[CR]dmask\f[R])
and files (\f[CR]fmask\f[R]).
For example, \f[CR]\-o fmask=077\f[R] would remove all permissions for
group and others from files.
.PD
.SH LOG MESSAGES
\f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] records log messages to the system logger
(\f[B]syslog\f[R]).
These messages can help troubleshoot issues, such as I/O errors or
archives that refuse to mount.
.PD
.PP
To read \f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R]\[cq]s log messages on most Linux
systems:
.IP
.EX
$ journalctl \-t fuse\-archive
.EE
.PD
.PP
Alternatively, you can run \f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] in the foreground
with the \f[CR]\-f\f[R] option to see log messages directly on your
terminal.
.PD
.PP
By default, \f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] writes \f[B]INFO\f[R] and
\f[B]ERROR\f[R] messages.
You can decrease the logging level to just \f[B]ERROR\f[R] messages with
the \f[CR]\-o quiet\f[R] option, or increase it to include
\f[B]DEBUG\f[R] messages with the \f[CR]\-o verbose\f[R] option.
.PD
.SS Redaction
To prevent sensitive file names from being recorded in the system logs,
use the \f[CR]\-o redact\f[R] option.
When enabled, file paths in log messages will be replaced with
\f[CR](redacted)\f[R].
.PD
.SH PERFORMANCE
Create a single \f[CR].tar.gz\f[R] file that is 256 MiB decompressed and
255 KiB compressed (the file just contains repeated 0x00 NUL bytes):
.IP
.EX
$ truncate \-\-size=256M zeroes
$ tar cfz zeroes\-256mib.tar.gz zeroes
.EE
.PD
.PP
Here are \f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R]\[cq]s timings:
.IP
.EX
$ time fuse\-archive zeroes\-256mib.tar.gz mnt
real    0m0.443s

$ dd if=mnt/zeroes of=/dev/null status=progress
268435456 bytes (268 MB, 256 MiB) copied, 0.836048 s, 321 MB/s

$ umount mnt
.EE
.PD
.PP
For comparison, here are \f[B]archivemount\f[R]\[cq]s timings:
.IP
.EX
$ time archivemount zeroes\-256mib.tar.gz mnt
real    0m0.581s

$ dd if=mnt/zeroes of=/dev/null status=progress
268435456 bytes (268 MB, 256 MiB) copied, 570.146 s, 471 kB/s

$ umount mnt
.EE
.PD
.PP
In this case, \f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] takes about the same time to load
the archive as \f[B]archivemount\f[R], but it is \f[B]\[ti]700×
faster\f[R] (0.83s vs.\ 570s) to copy out the decompressed contents.
This is because \f[B]fuse\-archive\f[R] fully caches the archive and
does not use \f[B]archivemount\f[R]\[cq]s \c
.UR https://github.com/cybernoid/archivemount/issues/21
quadratic complexity algorithm
.UE \c
\&.
.PD
.SH COMPARISON
.PD
.PP
